author: Wildcat 8

comment:
Everybody’s here hating on this movie, but
I remember when I saw it. Day before Thanksgiving, 2017. I was with my extended family, people I hadn’t seen in forever, friends who I had almost forgotten about. We all loved this movie. It had humor, it had action, it was uplifting and it made sense. On a sadder note, it was also the last time that I saw my cousin before he was deployed in the Marines, so I’ll always remember seeing his face light up watching this movie. The Snyder cut kind of hurts me because this right here was the version that I really liked and enjoyed with company. If you like the Snyder cut, that’s fine. Just remember that not everyone agrees with you.

comment: So from the look of it in Snyder's JL trailer, this scene definitely seemed expanded on. In the theatrical version (this video), he comes home, Steppenwolf attacks, takes the Motherbox and ditches, while Arthur engages in a conversation with Mera;  asks for his trident and is then on his merry way to find Steppenwolf. Now, from the very little we know from the trailer, Arthur returns to Atlantis, speaks to Mera and, in a very callous appearing way, leaves. Mera is then seen looking concerned and then you see the trident just laying there on the wet ground. What that tells me is that Arthur basically doesn't give a fuck, at least not right away. He doesn't bother with Steppenwolf until something else ends up motivating him to go find and help the League. Things like that are very essential for character development and adds to the overall arc of the character. Sad to see it didn't end up in the theatrical cut of the movie...

comment:
I believe that I can give answers to any plot holes or inconsistencies between this scene and the Aquaman solo film.

First, this location isn't explicitly stated to be Atlantis, so Arthur's reaction to seeing the kingdom for the first time in his film makes sense. This is also the first time that Arthur and Mera meet, which is why he asks for her name in his film, as he never asks for it here.

Then, the whole "bubble-talking" could have actually been a way for Mera to fully identify Arthur as Queen Atlanna's son, as it is explained in his film that only high-borns can breathe both on land and in water. She may have known what he looked like to some degree, but still needed to confirm the fact.

Also, Arthur's comments about his mother could be seen as some deep, persisting resentment for her leaving him, although he learns as a teenager that she was executed by the Atlanteans. He could still hate her for leaving in the first place which lead to her death, then between this film and his solo film, come to fully realise that she did it out of love for both him and his father.

Thoughts?

comment:
Sorry for TL;DR, but had a feeling there'd be comments about the whole "stupid air bubbles for talking" issue. I think it's more a lack of foresight or the directors (Snyder or Whedon, whichever directed this particular scene) not knowing what Wan was planning to do with Atlantean speech before the studio even started working on the film. Hell, an Aquaman movie was barely on the calendar before JL was being made, right? It's not like they have this whole elaborate masterplan like what we're spoiled with having regarding the Marvel movies akin to a Feige bigboss.

Anyway, I've now seen Aquaman's movie (twice in its opening weekend) and it's AMAZING. Currently grossed more $$$ than any other DCEU film and has the highest review rating as of my comment's posting. Despite how bad JL might be, I still enjoy it for how simple/basic/fun its story is. I also enjoy its mood (it's like I'm watching 1 of the animated JL films, especially with how easily the team comes together and the CGI looks a lot like cartoon action), the nostalgia fanservice it evokes and all the characters that make appearances be they core team members and various supporting characters. Personal preference, JL would probably be my 2nd fav DCEU movie to watch after Aquaman but for different reasons.

Having seen and enjoyed Aquaman, I thought back to this scene and everything has me looking at Mera in a completely different light. Not just because she's super beautiful or the true hero of Aquaman's movie (akin to how Samwise is the LotR trilogy true hero, ha). More than just the mother box guardian. I see the whole "stupid air bubbles" thing as a way for Mera to extend an accommodating "olive branch" to Arthur whom she assumes is more adjusted to speaking in air rather than in water. Plus, it puts her skills on display: hydrokinesis, budding diplomacy and her knowledge of his parentage. You can see here she's attempting to break peace with Arthur and his bitterness towards being an Atlantis outcast thought abandoned by his mother. If you go see his movie, you'll be in for a real treat on all that.

Maybe my reinterpretation of this scene covers up WB/DC's lack of foresight and other problems. But oh well, I can make it work for myself. I am someone that likes both Marvel AND DC (yes, it's possible to swing both ways) and I want them both to succeed.

I had a much better wording for all this in my mind but when home at laptop, it's all word vomit.
